<h1>The Euclidean Topology</h1>

<p>Let (<i>M,d</i>) be any metric space. and let <i>&tau;</i> be the collection of all subsets of <i>M</i> that are opn in the metric space sense. It follows from <a href="metric.html#theo">theorem 2.1.9</a> that this topology, called <b>metric topology on M</b>, or the <b>topology generated by <i>d</i></b>.</p>

<p>Metric spaces provide a rich source of examples of topological spaces. In fact, a large percentage of the topological spaces we beed to consider are actually subsets of Euclidean spaces; since every such subset is a metric space in its own right (with restriction of the Euclidean metric), it automatically inherits a ametric topology. We call this the <b>Euclidean topology</b>, and unless we specify otherwise, subsets of ℝ<sup><i>n</i></sup> are always considered as topological spaces with this topology. Thus our intuition regarding topological spaces relies heavily on our understanding of subsets of Euclidean space.</p>

<p>Even though most of the topological spaces we consider are (subsets of) metric spaces with their metric topologies, it is important to recognize that not every topology can be defined by a metric. A topological space <i>X</i> is said to be <b><i>metrizable</b></i> if its topology happens to be the metric topology generated by some metric on <i>X</i>. Some spaces that are not metrizable are described later.</p>

<p><b>Definition 2.1.1</b> A subset <i>S</i> of ℝ is said to be open in the <b>euclidean topology</b> on ℝ if it has the following property:</p>

<div class="eq">
<p>* For each <i>x</i> ∈ <i>S</i>, there exist <i>a, b</i> &in; ℝ, with <i>a</i> < <i>b</i>, such that <i>x</i> ∈ (<i>a, b</i>) ⊆ <i>S</i>.&emsp;□</p>
</div>

<p><b>Notation</b>. Whenever we refer to the topological space ℝ without specifying the topology, we mean ℝ with the euclidean topology.</p>

<p><b>Remark 2.1.2</b>. The “euclidean topology” <i>τ</i> is a topology.</p>

<p><b>Proof</b>.  We are required to show that <i>τ</i> satisfies conditions (i), (ii), and (iii) of definition <a href="topology.html">1.1.1</a>. Firstly, we show that ℝ ∈ <i>τ</i>. Let,  <I>x</i> &in; ℝ. If we put <i>a</i> = <i>x</i> − 1 and <i>b</i> = <i>x</i> + 1, then  <i>x</i> ∈ (<i>a, b</i>) ⊆ ℝ; that is, ℝ has property (∗) and so ℝ ∈ <i>τ</i> . Secondly, Ø ∈ <i>τ</i> as Ø has property (*) by default. <br> 
Now let {<i>A<sub>j</sub></i> :<i>j</i> ∈ <i>J</i>}, for some index set <i>J</i> , be a family of members of <i>τ</i> . Then we have to show that ⋃<sub><i>j</i>∈<i>J</i></sub> <i>A<sub>j</sub></i> ∈ <i>τ</i> ; that is, we have to show that ⋃<sub><i>j</i>∈<i>J</i></sub> <i>A<sub>j</sub></i> has property (∗). Let <i>x</i> ∈ U<sub>j ∈J</sub> <i>A<sub>j</sub></i> . Then <i>x</i> ∈ <i>A<sub>k</sub></i> , for some <i>k</i> ∈ <i>J</i> . As <i>A<sub>k</sub></i> ∈ <i>τ</i> , there exist <i>a</i> and <i>b</i> in ℝ with <i>a</i> < <i>b</i> such that <i>x</i> ∈ (<i>a, b</i>) ⊆ <i>A<sub>k</sub></i> . As <i>k</i> ∈ <i>J</i> , <i>A<sub>k</sub></i> ⊆ ⋃<sub><i>j</i> ∈ <i>J</i></sub> <i>A<sub>j</sub></i> and so <i>x</i> ∈ (<i>a, b</i>) ⊆ ⋃<sub><i>j</i>∈<i>J</i></sub> <i>A<sub>j</sub></i> . Hence ⋃<sub><i>j</i>∈<i>J</i></sub> <i>A<sub>j</sub></i> has property (∗) and thus is in <i>τ</i> , as required.<br>
Finally, let <i>A</i><sub>1</sub> and A<sub>2</sub> be in <i>&tau;</i>. We have to prove that <i>A</i><sub>1</sub> ∩ <i>A</i><sub>2</sub> &in; <i>&tau;</i>. So let <i>y</i> &in; <i>A</i><sub>1</sub> ∩ <i>A</i><sub>2</sub>. Then <i>y</i> &in; <i>A</i><sub>1</sub>. As <i>A</i><sub>1</sub> &in; <i>&tau;</i>, there exist <i>a</i> and <i>b</i> in ℝ with <i>a</i> &lt; <i>b</i> such that
<i>y</i> &in; (<i>a,b</i>) &subseteq; <i>A</i><sub>1</sub>. Also <i>y</i> &in; <i>A</i><sub>2</sub> &in; <i>&tau;</i>. So there exist <i>c</i> and <i>d</i> in ℝ with <i>c</i> &lt; <i>d</i> such 
that <i>y</i> ∈ (<i>c, d</i>) ⊆ <i>A</i><sub>2</sub> . Let <i>e</i> be the greater of <i>a</i> and <i>c</i>, and <i>f</i> the smaller of <i>b</i> and <i>d</i>. It is easily checked that <i>e</i> < <i>y</i> < <i>f</i>, and so <i>y</i> ∈ (<i>e, f</i> ). As (<i>e, f</i> ) ⊆ (<i>a, b</i>) ⊆ <i>A</i><sub>1</sub> and (<i>e, f</i> ) ⊆ (<i>c, d</i>) ⊆ <i>A</i><sub>2</sub> , we deduce that <i>y</i> ∈ (<i>e, f</i> ) ⊆ A<sub>1</sub> ∩ A<sub>2</sub> . Hence <i>A</i><sub>1</sub> ∩ <i>A</i><sub>2</sub> has  property (∗) and so is in <i>τ</i> .&emsp;□</p>

<h2>Order Topology</h2>

<p>Topologies can also be defined with respect to a total order. </p>

<p><b>Definition 1.2.1</b>. Let <i>X</i> a totally ordered set, and &le; linear order on <i>X</i>, define the open intervals of <i>X</i> to be the subsets</p>

<div class="eq">
<p>(<i>a,b</i>) = {<i>x</i> &in; <i>X</i> | <i>a</i> &lt; <i>x</i> &lt; <i>b</i>}<br>
(−&infin;,<i>a</i>) = {<i>x</i> &in; <i>X</i> | <i>x</i> &lt; <i>a</i>}<br>
(<i>a</i>,&infin;) = {<i>x</i> &in; <i>X</i> | <i>x</i> &gt; <i>a</i>}<br>
(−&infin;,&infin;) = <i>X</i></p>
</div>

<p>for <i>a,b</i> &in; <i>X</i>, and define the <i>open sets</i> of <i>X</i> to be the unions of arbitrary families of open intervals. The family of open sets so defined is a topology on <i>X</i>, called the <b>order topology</b>.</p>

<p>The usual linear ordering of ℝ generates an order topology on ℝ, known as <b>Euclidean topology</b>, in which open sets are unions of open intervals (<i>a,b</i>). </p>

<p><b>Proposition 1.3.1</b>. The set of open intervals (<i>a,b</i>) &subset; ℝ is a <a href="basis.html">basis</a>, ℬ, for the euclidean topology of ℝ, <i>τ</i><sub>ℝ</sub>. The “Euclidean topology” is a topology.</p>

<p><b>Proof</b>. We have to verify the topology axioms in <a href="topology.html">Definition 1.1.1</a>. Since one can write ℝ as the interval (−&infin;, +&infin;), ℝ &in; <i>τ</i><sub>ℝ</sub>. Ø is an empty union of members of ℬ and so Ø ∈ <i>τ</i><sub>ℝ</sub>. <br> To verify ii) and iii) in Definition 1.1.1 let</p>

<div class="eq">
<p><i>A</i> = ⋃<sub><sub><i>i</i> &in; <i>I</i></sub></sub> (<i>a<sub>i</sub>, b<sub>i</sub></i>), &emsp; <i>B</i> = ⋃<sub><sub><i>j</i> &in; <i>J</i></sub></sub> (<i>c<sub>j</sub>, d<sub>j</sub></i>), &emsp;...,&emsp; <i>Z</i> = ⋃<sub><sub><i>k</i> &in; <i>K</i></sub></sub> (<i>x<sub>k</sub>, y<sub>k</sub></i>)</p>
</div>

<p>a family of open sets; Then to prove ii), notice that</p>

<p><div class="eq">
<p><i>A</i> ∪ <i>B</i> ∪ ... ∪ <i>Z</i> = (⋃<sub><sub><i>i</i> &in; <i>I</i></sub></sub> (<i>a<sub>i</sub>, b<sub>i</sub></i>)) ∪ (⋃<sub><sub><i>j</i> &in; <i>J</i></sub></sub> (<i>c<sub>j</sub>, d<sub>j</sub></i>)) ∪ (⋃<sub><sub><i>k</i> &in; <i>K</i></sub></sub> (<i>x<sub>i</sub>, y<sub>i</sub></i>)) = ⋃<sub><sub><i>i</i> &in; <i>I</i>, <i>j</i> &in; <i>J</i>, <i>k</i> &in; <i>K</i></sub></sub> (<i>a<sub>i</sub>, b<sub>i</sub></i>) ∪ (<i>c<sub>j</sub>, d<sub>j</sub></i>) ∪ ... ∪ (<i>x<sub>k</sub>, y<sub>k</sub></i>)</p>
</div>

<p>still a union of open intervals (and can be generalized to unions of infinite open sets). For iii) by distributive law the intersection of two open sets is</p>

<p><div class="eq">
<p><i>A</i> ∩ <i>B</i> = (⋃<sub><sub><i>i</i> &in; <i>I</i></sub></sub> (<i>a<sub>i</sub>, b<sub>i</sub></i>)) ⋂ (⋃<sub><sub><i>j</i> &in; <i>J</i></sub></sub> (<i>c<sub>j</sub>, d<sub>j</sub></i>)) = ⋃<sub><sub><i>i</i> &in; <i>I</i>, <i>j</i> &in; <i>J</i></sub></sub> (<i>a<sub>i</sub>, b<sub>i</sub></i>) ∩ (<i>c<sub>j</sub>, d<sub>j</sub></i>)</p>
</div>

<p>is still a union of open intervals. Thus <i>τ</i><sub>ℝ</sub> is indeed a topology on ℝ. &emsp;□ </p>

<p>We call this topology the Euclidean topology or the standard topology or as well the usual topology on the real line.</p>

<p>It is important to note that while every open interval is an open set in ℝ, the converse is false. Not all open sets in ℝ are intervals. For example, the set (1, 4) ∪ (7, 9) is an open set in ℝ, but it is not an open interval.</p>

<p>So the collection of open intervals in ℝ is a basis for the Euclidean topology of ℝ. An open set in ℝ is obtained by forming an arbitrary union of open intervals, and a closed set in ℝ results from taking the complement in ℝ of such an open set. For example (0,2)  and (0, &infin;) are open in ℝ, whereas [0,2] and {0} are closed.</p>

